  						<table align=center cellpadding='3' width='85%'>
  <tr><td class='spti2'>PLAYER JOURNAL</td></tr>  <tr><td class='db'><font class='dbti'>A fateful encounter turns into a consuming passion</font> - Gardeltron Thundercrag</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'> </td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'><p>  Recently, I have been consumed by knowledge I gained of a quest to gain a spear of
such power that I can hardly imagine it.  I didn't believe that such a spear could exist until
I saw a powerful shaman carrying one, adorned with feathers and from which eminated a 
strange glow.  Despite my youth, I could think of nothing else than obtaining this spear.
I began to question others about it, until I found a certain gnome or halfing living on an
island in the Ocean of Tears who attacked when I spoke to him of the quest.  After defending
myself I found that a strange spirit in wolf form appeared and sent me on a long quest. That quest
led me to other spirits who gave me additional tasks to do.   After completing one such task
asked of me, I was given a strange magical shield. </p> <p>  When I delivered a 
jewel to yet another spirit in the Emerald Jungle, I was told that I had to find one of their 
brethren who had been lead astray by a very powerful dark elf, whose name I found out
later was Mistmoore.  I visited his castle in my 41st season, and found the Black Dire spoken
of by the spirit.  I asked for help from those who were engaged in fighting various mobs
in the envrions around Mistmoore's Castle, and was hailed by a very powerful wizard.  He
was determined to kill the Black Dire by standing on top of Mistmoore's Castle and blasting
it with his powerful spells.  I was dubious that such a thing could be done, realizing that
the Black Dire was evil and if I tried to talk to it, I would instantly be killed.  And though I
had some doubts about it, I joined the wizard on top of the castle and asked if he would let 
me inspect the spirit's corpse if somehow he could overpower it.  He told me that I would
have to earn that right by using may own inferior shamanic magic to cast my less effective
spells on the Black Dire.  In my immense desire to serve the spirits and somehow have
them show me the way to find the powerful spear of fate, I consented to help.  We cast on the
Dire from the relative safety of the castle roof, although we found that he had learned to
cast the spells that many shadowknights learn.  I healed us both and continued to cast my
best damage spells, though I knew I was doing much less damage than the wizard.
Eventually, after what seemed like half a day, Black Dire began 
to weaken.  We were meditating and casting as fast as we could, and soon the Black Dire
began to retreat, but only a short distance.  I remember quite vividly that when the Black
Dire was obviously near death, I stood up, trembling, and cast yet another cold damage
spell.  Suddenly, the Black Dire collapsed.  Using levitate, I literally flew to the corpse, greatly
saddened that one of the True Spirits I had been serving was now dead.  I took its pelt back to the 
sentinel spirit in the Emerald Jungle, who cried ove the loss of his once faithful companion.
He fashioned a pair of magical boots from the hide and gave them to me to remind me of
the loss that we both felt.  He then sent me off to the City of Mist to do yet another
errand.</p>

<p>  I cannot imagine where this quest will take me.  I have noticed in struggling to accomplish
the next errand that each step in this quest becomes harder.  Death seems to loom over
me constantly, and I now humbly realize how lucky I am to have come this far.  Although the
shield and boots I obtained have been exceedingly useful to me, I know now it will be many
seasons filled with pain, suffering, and hardship before I can even hope to be worthy of this
fabled spear of fate.  But my whole being is consumed with pursuing it, and I know I will never
rest until I have it.  Indeed, what once seemed like yet another adventure, has now become
a consuming passion.  Yet I take some small consolation in the fact that I know of others who
have the spear in their possession.  So I may yet claim it as my own.  But until then, I walk in 
the valley of the shadow of death, never knowing when or if my fate will be sealed by death
without ever having gained the spear.  May the Tribunal judge my weak soul with mercy.  </p></td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db2'><a href='view_profile.asp?Action=Journal&Id=33000'>Return to Gardeltron's Journal</a></td></tr>
